00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:09.250
That's a function that describes how

21
00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:13.745
the lens transforms the phase fronts that are incident on it.

22
00:01:13.745 --> 00:01:15.640
And remember, optical path length,

23
00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:19.105
which we derived or defined before, is simply, N times L,

24
00:01:19.105 --> 00:01:24.398
or more formally, the integral of N along the ray,

25
00:01:24.398 --> 00:01:29.225
and that tells us something about the phase that's accumulated along the ray.

26
00:01:29.225 --> 00:01:33.955
Now, we could do that through a lot of techniques but the technique which is

27
00:01:33.955 --> 00:01:38.245
really convenient for doing this calculation is Fermat's principle.

28
00:01:38.245 --> 00:01:41.500
And this is an example of where knowing these deeper laws,

29
00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:44.260
like Fermat's principle, allows you to do things very,

30
00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:46.380
very simply and quickly.

