00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:47.560
So, what we are going to do is,

32
00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:52.985
we are going to imagine launching some light off of an object in multiple directions.

33
00:01:52.985 --> 00:01:56.445
It goes through a lens and converges back to an image.

34
00:01:56.445 --> 00:02:01.540
Fermat's principle states that no matter what direction we shoot the ray,

35
00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:04.690
by the time they all get back to the image,

36
00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:08.770
the total optical path length, or transit time,

37
00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:11.610
should be invariant to the ray direction,

38
00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:15.750
it should be stationary using the language of mathematics.

39
00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:18.005
And this kind of makes physical sense.

40
00:02:18.005 --> 00:02:22.780
If you think about a set of waves converging toward the image here,

41
00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:24.575
if they weren't all in phase,

42
00:02:24.575 --> 00:02:27.505
we wouldn't have constructive interference at the image point,

43
00:02:27.505 --> 00:02:30.900
and actually generate a converging spherical wave there,

44
00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:33.065
so that's the physical interpretation of it.

45
00:02:33.065 --> 00:02:35.135
The calculation is quite simple.

46
00:02:35.135 --> 00:02:36.430
On the left hand side,

47
00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:38.440
we're going to simply calculate

48
00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:42.250
the optical path length of a ray that goes right down the axis, there's NT,

49
00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.310
with the minus sign,

50
00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:44.526
of course, because this is a minus distance,

51
00:02:44.526 --> 00:02:50.130
negative distance, and then continues on to the image N prime T prime.

52
00:02:50.130 --> 00:02:55.420
Now, I could have some thickness of the lens right there and that's just a constant,

53
00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:58.825
constants don't matter because they don't change the shape of the wave front,

54
00:02:58.825 --> 00:03:00.990
so I'm going to set that equal to zero.

55
00:03:00.990 --> 00:03:02.265
I could have put a constant here,

56
00:03:02.265 --> 00:03:04.055
wouldn't have made any difference.

57
00:03:04.055 --> 00:03:08.865
I'm beginning to set that optical path length equal to a ray,

58
00:03:08.865 --> 00:03:13.520
to that of a ray that goes up to some arbitrary distance R and back down.

59
00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:18.365
So I calculate new distances based on that hypotenuse of that triangle,

60
00:03:18.365 --> 00:03:20.945
the same thing over on the right hand side.

61
00:03:20.945 --> 00:03:24.170
And now, I add in a correction factor.

62
00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:27.895
This must be what the lens does, what extra phase,

63
00:03:27.895 --> 00:03:32.930
what extra optical path length it adds in order to make this condition true,

64
00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:35.560
in order to make Fermat's principal happen.

65
00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:39.285
Because we're going to be paraxial here,

66
00:03:39.285 --> 00:03:42.770
or first order design as in the name of the course,

67
00:03:42.770 --> 00:03:45.740
we are going to take these angles to be sufficiently

68
00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:50.610
small that we can take sine theta and tan theta equal to theta.

69
00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:56.075
Snell's law simplifies N theta equals N theta,

70
00:03:56.075 --> 00:04:00.110
and in the case of these square root functions here,

71
00:04:00.110 --> 00:04:04.560
we'll take the binomial approximation and just keep the first term.

72
00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:10.900
So, that's all the same approximation at the small angle paraxial approximation.

73
00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:13.543
So, when we do that, we get terms will cancel out,

74
00:04:13.543 --> 00:04:16.490
you see the NT here and the N prime T prime,

