00:05:14.965 --> 00:05:16.465
some constant in here,

95
00:05:16.465 --> 00:05:22.850
that would represent the optical path length N times L at the center of the lens.

96
00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:26.275
For positive focal length lens, F,

97
00:05:26.275 --> 00:05:30.585
then we see that quadratically going away from the axis,

98
00:05:30.585 --> 00:05:32.295
the lens gets thinner.

99
00:05:32.295 --> 00:05:35.460
The optical path length decreases.

100
00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:38.690
That makes sense, that's what a lens should do.

101
00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:40.740
If, of course, the focal length was negative,

102
00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:42.035
the opposite would occur,

103
00:05:42.035 --> 00:05:45.790
and it would get thicker going away from the origin,

104
00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:50.359
and it does that proportional to 1 over F. So,

105
00:05:50.359 --> 00:05:52.930
the quantity 1 over F is powerful enough,

106
00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:56.085
is important enough that we need a name for it, we're going to use this a lot.

107
00:05:56.085 --> 00:05:57.675
We call it the power.

108
00:05:57.675 --> 00:05:59.790
It's just a convenient variable.

109
00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:01.695
It's got units of one over meters,

110
00:06:01.695 --> 00:06:03.128
and that's useful enough,

111
00:06:03.128 --> 00:06:05.940
we give it its own name, in optics, called diopters.

112
00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:07.330
And if you have eyeglasses,

113
00:06:07.330 --> 00:06:08.750
you've heard of diopters.

114
00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:13.180
One diopter of correction is a relatively weak correction, for example.

115
00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:15.750
So, a powerful lens,

116
00:06:15.750 --> 00:06:17.665
a large number here,

117
00:06:17.665 --> 00:06:20.410
that meaning a short focal length,

118
00:06:20.410 --> 00:06:25.880
would mean that the change of the optical path length with radius was vast.

119
00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.230
Powerful lenses are very curved,

120
00:06:29.230 --> 00:06:31.980
weak lenses, small power,

121
00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:34.900
few diopters, a one-diopter eyeglass lens,

122
00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:39.950
for example, are relatively shallow in their curvature.

123
00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:43.115
So, powerful lenses are lots of curvature,

124
00:06:43.115 --> 00:06:46.977
weak lenses are little curvature.

125
00:06:46.977 --> 00:06:49.655
That power concept is useful in lots of ways,

126
00:06:49.655 --> 00:06:51.340
but here's the first one.

127
00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:54.610
We can restate our Gaussian thin lens equation by

128
00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:58.754
replacing 1 over F with this power, Phi,

129
00:06:58.754 --> 00:07:02.140
and we can now interpret that as

130
00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:06.930
a transformation of the radius of curvature of the lens because of the wavefront.

131
00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:10.100
Here, we have a radiating spherical wave and at the lens,

132
00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:13.900
it would have a radius of curvature equal to T. It gets

133
00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:19.315
transformed into a converging spherical wave with radius of curvature T prime.

134
00:07:19.315 --> 00:07:20.980
What this equation tells us,

135
00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:23.845
a different way of thinking about the Gaussian thin lens equation,

136
00:07:23.845 --> 00:07:27.280
is that the lens simply adds power,

137
00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:28.687
in the case of a positive lens,

138
00:07:28.687 --> 00:07:31.420
that transforms this radius of curvature,

139
00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:33.520
which would be negative in our sign convention,

140
00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:36.810
to this radius of curvature, which would be positive.

141
00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:40.270
If, for example, the object is just at the focal length,

142
00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:42.160
such that the radius of curvature of

143
00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.131
the emerging spherical wave is equal to the power of the lens,

144
00:07:46.131 --> 00:07:49.045
then we get an infinite radius of curvature,

145
00:07:49.045 --> 00:07:52.820
which is consistent with having the object at the front focal plane.

146
00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:57.280
This is a slightly more sophisticated way to think about what lenses do,

147
00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:00.870
they transform radii of curvature.